1. Introduction¶

In an economy, the term liquidation is used to define the process of the end of a firm and distributing its assets to claimants. The number of liquidated firms plays a crucial role to analyze and make decisions about the economy. From governers to financial institutions the statistics is used behind the economic decisions like credit allocation decisions, macroecenomic decisions etc. However, the statistics is announced after the month passed which causes the decisions are made with old data. Therefore, the future values of liquadated firm number is important for some firms, governers etc.

In this study, I will build a linear regression model that forecasts the number of liquidated firms in the next month. Throughout my analysis, I will first handle the issues of the target variable like seosanality, trend, etc. Than, I will try do improve my model by adding some other features like USD/TRY, commercial_credit_int_rate, reel_sector_confidence_index, general_business_situation, general_economic_situation_present, "general_economic_situation_expectation".

From the lineplot above, we clearly see that there is strong seasonality in our data and we observe decreasing trend over time. Therefore, I will include both seasonality and trend components to my model. Also, we see a fall in COVID-19 quarantina period, so I will add is_covid columns which is 1 for march and april of 2020 and 0 for other dates.

2.3. Build the base model¶

I will build the base model with trend, seasonality and covid period:

In [6]:
### Add Trend
log_data["trend"] = list(range(1, len(data)+1))

### Add Seasonality
log_data["month"] = log_data.index.month
log_data.month = pd.Categorical(log_data.month)

### Add Covid period
log_data["is_covid"] = 0
log_data.loc[[dt.date(2020,3,1), dt.date(2020,4,1)], "is_covid"] = 1

### Add Constant to log_data:
log_data["const"] = 1

From the pair plots and the heat map we see that correlations among 'general_economic_situation_present' and 'general_economic_situation_expectation' and USD/TRY are very high which will cause multicollinearity in the model. Since there is a high correlation between them, one of the three features can explain the others. Therefore, I will drop "general_economic_situation_expectation" and "general_economic_situation_present" which are probably shaped by movements of USD/TRY.

I will also drop "reel sector confidence index" which is corralated with "general business situation".

3. Conclusion¶

In this homework I have established a model that can predict next month's liquadated firm count. In the model, I have handled the monthly seasonality by adding dummy variables for each month. There was a falling trend in the data and it is handled by adding a trend feature which is a sequence from 1 to 107. The target variable, liquadated firm count, was seem to be affected by COVID-19 period and 15 July coup attack. In order to handle the errors in those periods, the variables is_covid and is_coup_attack added to model which are 1 during the relevant periods and 0 for other times. Those 2 variables are important to model extra-ordinary situations on liquadated firm count and can be used in other for example pandemic periods. Only by looking those variables, we got a good model but in order to improve our model further, I have checked

1. USD/TRY excahnge rate, 
2. commercial credit interest rate, 
3. real sector confidence index, 
4. general bussiness situation and 
5. present general economic situation,
6. expected general economic situation

those six variables with my data. I did not used 3, 5, 6 since those were corralated with some other feautures which would cause multicollinearity. Finally, the model has improved with those features and our final model has R-squared: 0.896, Adj. R-squared: 0.874 and Prob (F-statistic): 1.40e-34. Which are good enough for a model. Therefore, can be used for predictions.
